<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,151,2013]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<taxonomicName box="[151,389,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Colobaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis box="[151,389,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Colobaea americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the smallest known species of 
<taxonomicName box="[776,924,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Sciomyzidae</taxonomicName>
, with field-collected adult flies ranging from only 1.8 to 2.0 mm in length and with some laboratory-reared adult flies measuring only 
<quantity box="[1137,1223,187,213]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="1.2">1.2 mm</quantity>
in length. The species is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[343,473,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Heleomyzidae" genus="Opomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="distincta">
<emphasis box="[343,362,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[377,473,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">distincta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Zetterstedt" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[488,633,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Colobaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pectoralis">
<emphasis box="[488,507,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[521,633,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">pectoralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityYear="1923" box="[695,827,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Colobaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctata">
<emphasis box="[695,714,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[729,827,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">punctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in color pattern and in development of the dorsobasal aristal setulae. 
<bibRefCitation author="Steyskal, G. C." box="[319,496,258,285]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="59 - 65" refId="ref46797" refString="Steyskal, G. C. (1954) Colobaea and Hedria, two genera of Sciomyzidae new to America (Diptera: Acalyptratae). Canadian Entomologist, 86, 59 - 65. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / Ent 8660 - 2" type="journal article" year="1954">Steyskal (1954)</bibRefCitation>
figured the antenna and wing but did not describe or figure the male postabdomen, which has not yet been figured, although both the male and female abdomens were described in detail by 
<bibRefCitation author="Murphy, W. L. &amp; Mathis, W. N. &amp; Knutson, L. V." pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="1 - 299" refId="ref45469" refString="Murphy, W. L., Mathis, W. N. &amp; Knutson, L. V. (2018) Comprehensive taxonomic, faunistic, biological, and geographic inventory and analysis of the Sciomyzidae (Diptera: Acalyptratae) of the Delmarva region and nearby states in eastern North America. Zootaxa, 4430 (1), 1 - 299. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4430.1.1" type="journal article" year="2018">
Murphy 
<emphasis box="[151,200,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al</emphasis>
. (2018)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,151,2013]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
In 
<taxonomicName box="[229,382,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Colobaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis box="[229,248,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[262,382,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the only species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zetterstedt" authorityYear="1837" box="[611,720,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Colobaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[611,720,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Colobaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for which chromosomes have been numbered, the diploid number of chromosomes is 12 (
<bibRefCitation author="Boyes, J. W. &amp; Knutson, L. V. &amp; Jan, K. Y. &amp; Berg, C. O." box="[459,663,403,430]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="331 - 356" refId="ref43265" refString="Boyes, J. W., Knutson, L. V., Jan, K. Y. &amp; Berg, C. O. (1969) Cytotaxonomic studies of Sciomyzidae (Diptera: Acalyptratae). Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 88 (3), 331 - 356. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3224701" type="journal article" year="1969">
Boyes 
<emphasis box="[539,589,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">et al</emphasis>
. 1969
</bibRefCitation>
), with five metacentric pairs of autosomes. The X allosome is rather small. This configuration is similar to that of some species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Becker, 1919" authorityName="Becker" authorityYear="1919" box="[834,1147,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Parectinocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[834,993,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Parectinocera</emphasis>
Becker, 1919
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Robineau-Desvoidy" authorityYear="1830" box="[1200,1318,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Pherbellia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1200,1318,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Pherbellia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but unlike that of any examined species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Lioy, 1864" authorityName="Lioy" authorityYear="1864" box="[512,770,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Pteromicra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[512,639,475,500]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Pteromicra</emphasis>
Lioy, 1864
</taxonomicName>
, in which the diploid number is 10.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
